}}, {{t+check|br|sivienn|f-s}}, {{q|2}} {{t-check|br|sivied|p}}\n* Cebuano: {{t-check|ceb|estroberi}}\n* Franco-Provençal: {{t-check|frp|fraga}}\n* Hiligaynon: {{q|1}} {{t-check|hil|istroberi}}, {{t-check|hil|lumboy}}\n* Hindi: {{t+check|hi|हिसालू}} {{q|1}}\n* Indonesian: {{t+check|id|arbei}} {{q|1}}, {{t+check|id|buah arbei}}\n* Interlingua: {{q|1}} {{t+check|ia|fraga}}\n* Inuktitut: {{t-check|iu|ᐊᖅᐱᓕᒐᖅ}} {{q|1}}\n* Korean: {{t+check|ko|딸기}}\n* Latin: {{t-check|la|fragaria|f}} {{q|1|2}}\n* Lombard: {{t+check|lmo|magiostra|f}}\n* Luxembourgish: {{q|1}} {{t+check|lb|Äerdbier|f}}, {{q|2}} {{t-check|lb|Äerdbeerpflanz|f}}\n* Occitan: {{t+check|oc|majofa|f}}\n* Persian: {{t+check|fa|توت فرنگی}}, {{t-check|fa|چلیک خوراکی}}\n* Piedmontese: {{q|2}} {{t-check|pms|fròla|f}}\n* Romani: {{t-check|rom|hamtsùrus}}\n* Rwanda-Rundi: {{t-check|rw|inkere}}\n* Thai: {{t-check|th|ผลสตรอว์เบอร์รี่|tr=pŏn sàdtror-berrêe}}\n* Urdu: {{t-check|ur|شلیک|tr=šulīk}}\n* Vietnamese: {{t+check|vi|trái}}, {{t-check|vi|cây dâu tây}}\n* Welsh: {{t-check|cy|mefysen|f}}, {{t-check|cy|syfïen|f}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Adjective===\n{{en-adj|er}}\n\n# Containing or having the flavor of strawberries.\n#: {{ux|en|I'd like a large '''strawberry''' shake.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|journal=[[w:Chicago Tribune|Chicago Daily Tribune]]|volume=C| issue=110| date=8 May 1941| page=8| pageurl=https://archive.org/details/per_chicago-daily-tribune_1941-05-08_100_110/page/n7/mode/1up| passage=We sing you a song of the '''strawberriest''' Strawberry Ice Cream on earth.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|journal=w:St. Louis Post-Dispatch|volume=100|issue=243|location=St. Louis, Mo.|date=5 May 1948|page=3D|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/per_st-louis-post-dispatch_1948-05-05_100_243/page/n40/mode/1up|passage=At any rate, you will agree with me that this is the “'''strawberriest''' tastin’&nbsp;” pie that you’ve ever tasted.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|journal=[[w:McCall's|McCall’s]]|volume=LXXXVIII|issue=9|month=June|year=1961|page=47|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/sim_rosie_1961-06_88_9/page/47/mode/1up|passage=Sixty seconds of boiling, and you’ll be admiring the '''strawberriest''' strawberry jam you ever tasted.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=w:Basil Cottle|title=The Penguin Dictionary of Surnames|publisher=w:Penguin Books|year=1967|year_published=1969|page=109|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/penguindictionar00cott/page/109/mode/1up|passage=Fraser Recorded in Scotland in mid-1100s as ''de Frisselle'', ''de Freseliere'', ''de Fresel'', as if from a place in France, and Sir Simon F— (executed 1306) is referred to as ''Simond Frysel''; first element ?‘ash tree’ {{smallcaps|of}}, the –er ?to make it ‘'''strawberrier'''’ – a pun on the three silver cinquefoils or ''fraises'' in their armorials.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|journal=[[w:Ladies' Home Journal|Ladies’ Home Journal]]|volume=LXXXV|location=Philadelphia, Pa.|publisher=[[w:Curtis Publishing Company|The Curtis Publishing Company]]|month=March|year=1968|page=122|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/ladieshomejourna85janwyet/page/n345/mode/1up|passage=With at least 26 berries like these in every jar like this, how must Kraft Pure Strawberry Preserves taste? The '''strawberriest''' best!}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Glenn Andrews|title=Impromptu Cooking|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=[[w:Atheneum Books|Atheneum]]|year=1973|page=216|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/impromptucooking00andr/page/216/mode/1up|isbn=0-689-10581-9|passage=And your strawberry ice cream can be the '''strawberriest''' and your peach ice cream the peachiest.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|author=sue ellen farmer|journal=The Student|month=fall|year=1975|page=thirty-seven|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/wakefo_thestudent7576/page/n40/mode/1up|column=2|passage=lessons exist because frozen strawberries in store are easier to pick but wild strawberries taste '''strawberrier'''.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=[[w:Barbara Halloran Gibbons|Barbara [Halloran] Gibbons]]|title=The International Slim Gourmet Cookbook|publisher=[[w:Harper (publisher)|Harper & Row]]|year=1978|page=324|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/internationalsli00gibb/page/324/mode/1up|isbn=0-06-011507-6|passage=My '''strawberriest''' of strawberry sauces was simply strawberries, whirred until chunky in the blender, then spooned over vanilla ice cream (or, in this case, low-fat ice milk).}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|journal=w:Family Circle|date=5 June 1979|page=41|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/family-circle-magazine-1979-06-05/page/41/mode/1up|passage={{ruby|Now Jell-[O](BRAND)® Strawberry Flavor Gelatin tastes even '''Strawberrier'''.}}}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=[[w:Barbara Halloran Gibbons|Barbara [Halloran] Gibbons]]|title=Slim Gourmet Sweets and Treats|location=New York, N.Y.| publisher=[[w:Harper (publisher)|Harper & Row]]|year=1982|page=11|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/slimgourmetsweet00gibb/page/11/mode/1up| isbn=0-06-015057-2| passage=When used to sweeten out-of-season California strawberries, the berries are not only sweeter but “'''strawberrier''',” with a flavor more like home-grown or field-ripened fruit.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Les Fox; Sue Fox|title=The Beanie Baby Handbook|publisher=West Highland Publishing Company|year=1998| page=161| pageurl=https://archive.org/details/beaniebabyhandbo00foxl_0/page/161/mode/1up|isbn=1892141-01-9| passage=Kiwi, Kiwi, chirping bright / In the forests of the night / Only a Kiwi could be merrier / About shortcake so '''strawberrier'''!}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=w:Nigella Lawson|title=How to Be a Domestic Goddess: Baking and the Art of Comfort Cooking| location=London| publisher=w:Chatto & Windus| year=2000|page=347|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/howtobedomesticg0000laws_i3l2/page/347/mode/1up| isbn=0 7011 6888 9| passage=It occurred to me when I was last making the strawberries in dark syrup from ''How to Eat'' that there was no reason why I couldn’t use the balsamic vinegar – which provides the darkness and really does seem to make the strawberries '''strawberrier''' – when making jam.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|journal=[[w:Sunset (magazine)|Sunset]]|month=May|year=2004|page=127|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/sunset212213maysout/page/n140/mode/1up|passage=It’s the '''strawberriest''' shortcake ever.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Rowan Clifford|title=Rodeo Ron and His Milkshake Cows|url=https://archive.org/details/rodeoronhismilks0000clif/page/n18/mode/1up|publisher=Borzoi Books|year=2005|isbn=0-375-93195-3|passage=Down leaped Ron and milked the frothiest, fruitiest, '''strawberriest''' milkshake anybody had ever tasted.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Annette Yates|title=Ice Cream Made Easy: Homemade Recipes for Ice Cream Machines|publisher=Right Way|year=2009| page=39| pageurl=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780716023166/page/39/mode/1up|isbn=978-0-7160-2316-6|passage=“The '''strawberriest''' ice cream I have ever tasted!” was the verdict of my daughter Lindsay.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Hartley Pool|title=Stranger in Taiwan|publisher=Revenge Ink| year=2011| page=77| pageurl=https://archive.org/details/strangerintaiwan0000pool/page/77/mode/1up| isbn=978-0-9565119-6-6| passage=Mind you, I have to admit they were three of the '''strawberriest''' looking strawberries I have ever seen.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Caroline Green|title=Hold Your Breath|publisher=Piccadilly Press|year=2013|page=125|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/holdyourbreath0000gree_f7m2/page/125/mode/1up|isbn=978 1 84812 170 6|passage=It was the '''strawberriest''' strawberry ever.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|journal=[[w:Front (magazine)|Front]]|issue=177|month=January|year=2013|page=38|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/frontmagazine177/page/n37/mode/1up|passage=HANNAH SAYS: “Wow, these are incredibly juicy. These are the '''strawberriest''' things in the world. They’re more strawberry[-]ish than actual strawberries. They’re incredible!”}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Daniel Neman|title=Strawberry spectacular|journal=w:Hartford Courant|volume=CLXXXVI|date=9 June 2022|section=4|page=4|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/0ba-56888-3670-4f-77-8772-8cbbe-566d-890/page/n35/mode/1up|column=1|passage=Right now, strawberries are their '''strawberriest'''.}}\n# Flavored with [[ethyl methylphenylglycidate]], an artificial compound which is said to resemble the taste of strawberries.\n# Of a color similar to the color of strawberry-flavoured products.\n#: {{ux|en|The '''strawberry''' lipstick matched his outfit.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Ida Liberkowski; Cynthia Malizia|title=Along the Amalfi Drive|publisher=w:Lulu.com| year=2006| page=282| isbn=9781847285065| passage=They are, at once, beautiful and curious, with their translucent white skin and '''strawberriest''' blond hair, looking like a group of Wagner’s Valkyrie lost in a Puccini opera.}}\n\n====Synonyms====\n* {{l|en|strawberryish}}\n* {{l|en|strawberrylike}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top|flavour}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|jahodový}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|jordbær}}-\n* Dutch: {{t|nl|aardbeien-}}\n* Finnish: {{t|fi|[[mansikka]]-}} {{qualifier|in compounds}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Erdbeere|alt=Erdbeer-}}, {{t|de|erdbeerig}}\n* Japanese: {{t|ja|[[苺]][[味]]の|tr=いちごあじの, ichigoaji no}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|truskawkowy}}\n* Portuguese: {{t|pt|[[de]] [[morango]]}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|земляни́чный}}, {{t+|ru|клубни́чный}}\n* Slovak: {{t+|sk|jahodový}}\n* Swedish: {{t|sv|jordgubbs-}}\n* Turkish: {{t|tr|çilekli}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t|uk|суни́чний|f}}, {{t|uk|полуни́чний|f}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|color}}\n* Danish: {{t|da|jordbærfarvet}}\n* Finnish: {{t|fi|mansikanpunainen}}\n* Ido: {{t|io|fragea}}\n* Japanese: {{t|ja|[[苺]][[色]]の|tr=いちごいろの, ichigoiro no}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|truskawkowy}}\n* Slovak: {{t|sk|červený ako jahoda}}\n* Swedish: {{t|sv|jordgubbsfärgad}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To gather strawberries.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1994|title=New England Review|volume=16|page=35\n|passage=We '''strawberried''' in Michigan woods with our fat nanny, and in spring we gathered sand dollars on Daytona, passed smiling into Kodachrome.}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To turn a dark pinkish-red.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1986|author=Les Whitten|title=Sometimes a Hero|page=352\n|passage=My hips and elbows were '''strawberrying''' painfully.}}\n\n===See also===\n* {{l|en|arbutus}}\n* {{l|en|Carolina allspice}}\n* {{l|en|hautboy}}\n{{list:reds/en}}\n\n===References===\n<references/>\n* {{R:OneLook}}\n* {{R:Century 1911}}\n* {{pedia}}\n* {{specieslite|Fragaria|i=1}}\n* {{comcatlite|Fragaria|i=1}}\n* {{R:Greens|id=o65praq|pos=n}}\n\n{{C|en|Berries|Rose family plants|Prostitution}}"}}